diose Palace of Justice and the Palazzo del Popolo d’Italia, through which Mussolini intended to enhance the city’s image and solidify fascism’s presence in Milan. Maulsby establishes the extent to which Milan’s economic structure, social composition, and cultural orientation affected Il Duce’s plans for the city, demonstrating the influences on urban development that were beyond the control of the fascist regime. By placing Milan’s urban change in its historic context, this book expands our understanding of the relationship between fascism and the modern city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArchitecture and statexHistoryx20th centuryxItalyxMilan. 0aArchitecture and statezItalyzMilanxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchitecturexHistoryx20th centuryxItalyxMilan. 0aArchitecturezItalyzMilanxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascism and architecturexHistoryx20th centuryxItalyxMilan. 0aFascism and architecturezItalyzMilanxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic buildingsxHistoryx20th centuryxItalyxMilan. 0aPublic buildingszItalyzMilanxHistoryy20th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266525540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442665255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442665255.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles